  "success": true,
  "message": "Message sent to team-lead's inbox",
  "routing": {
    "sender": "wittgenstein-expert",
    "senderColor": "blue",
    "target": "@team-lead",
    "targetColor": "red",
    "summary": "YES — Translator's Afterword, solves spoiler problem",
    "content": "**YES** — include a Translator's Afterword.\n\nThe placement solves the spoiler problem completely: the reader has already undergone the philosophical experiments, so cross-traditional connections and scholarly positioning now *enrich* rather than *pre-empt* the experience. From a Wittgensteinian perspective, this is the right sequence -- first you play the language game, then you can reflect on its grammar. A Translator's Afterword (rather than a critical or editorial one) is the natural choice because the translator is the one who has navigated every terminological and experiential decision; they are best positioned to explain what was preserved, what was transformed, and how the work connects to philosophical traditions the reader may already know. It would be the place to discuss connections to Wittgenstein, Husserl, Buddhist thought, Kant, etc. -- all the things that would have been spoilers in a Foreword but become illuminating after the reader has their own experiential basis to evaluate them against."
  }
}
